people seek from their transportation systems. While the concept of accessibility has been around for the better part of a century, From Mobility to Accessibility shows that the accessibility shift is compelled by the fundamental purpose of transportation. The book argues that the shift would be transformative to the practice of both transportation and land-use planning but is impeded by many conceptual obstacles regarding the nature of accessibility and its potential for guiding development of the built environment. By redefining success in transportation, the book provides city planners, decisionmakers, and scholars a path to reforming the practice of transportation and land-use planning in modern cities and metropolitan areas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aCity planningzUnited States. 0aCity planning. 0aLand use, UrbanxPlanning. 0aLand use, UrbanzUnited StatesxPlanning. 0aUrban transportationxPlanning. 0aUrban transportationzUnited StatesxPlanning. 4aPublic Policy. 4aTransportation. 4aUrban Studies.  aTransport Planning.  aU.S. urban planning.  aaccessibility in social-equity .  aaccessibility land use .  aaccessibility metrics .  aaccessibility models .  aaccessibility planning .  aaccessibility shift.  aaccessibility studies case studies .  aaccessibility thinking.  aaccessibility transportation .  aaccessibility-oriented planning.  aaccessible urban design.  abuilding accessibility .  acity planning .  acity planning accessibility standards .  acity planning and accessibility studies .  acity planning manuals .  aevaluating regional transportation performance.  ahow to be more accessible .  aimprove mobility .  aimprove transportation mobility .  ainclusive transportation .  aland use accessibility studies .  aland-use planning.  ametropo